Introduction to Open Data Science - Course Project

About the project

As the name implies, Introduction to Open Data Science (IODS) is an introductory data science course at the University of Helsinki. The purpose of the course is to introduce the students to use of open research tools and open data, state of the art of data science tools RStudio, Rmarkdown and GitHub, and last, teach multivariate statistical methods and data visualization.

Personally, the main focus of my research is time series analysis of magnetically active stars, and therefore my statistics toolbox consists mostly of single variable methods. I have also mainly used Python for my programming and data analysis needs, so for these two reasons alone, I am quite excited about the course and hoping that the skills I will learn will be inspirational and provide new possibilities for my own research. The repository for the personal course work can be found here.

Exercise 2 - Reading in data and analyzing it with a multiple regression model

In this exercise we analyze a dataset related to introductory statistics course Johdatus yhteiskuntatilastotieteeseen, held in autumn 2014. The dataset contains information about the attendants, their age, gender, exam points, numerical values from the answers to questionnaire held at the course, etc.. The dataset used in this exercise uses a subset of the original dataset.

The dataset is first preprocessed (wrangled) by running a script create_learning2014.R found at the GIT-repository and then visualized in order to gain some insight into the structure of the data. We are interested in how different variables could explain how well the student did on the course exam. I will select a few explanatory variables from the dataset that are used to model the dependency between the exam scores and the said variables. Last part is the model validation, where the results from the modeling are reviewed, and I will discuss, whether or not the results are reliable.

Visualizing and exploring the data

In the next code snippet, the data that was wrangled by using the script create_learning2014.R is loaded into a variable learning2014. After that, I plot the data by using routine ggpairs. It creates scatter plots of the various items contained in the data, their distributions and calculates the correlation coefficient between the different variables.

learning2014 <- read.table("./data/learning2014.txt",header=TRUE)
# First, check that the structure of the data is OK
summary(learning2014)
##     gender               Age           Attitude         Points

According to the summary, everything seems to be in order, the dataset contains 166 entries of seven variables, just as there should be.

In addition to the self-explanatory, the variable Attitude reflects the general attitude of the attendant towards statistics. Stra, deep, and surf are mean scores from three categories of questions that reflect three different learning strategies. Stra comes from strategic learning approach, surf reflects a superficial attitude towards learning, and deep a more deep, profound learning approach.

#Then, visualize the data

#get access to gglot2 and GGally libraries
library(GGally)
## Loading required package: ggplot2

##   method from   
##   +.gg   ggplot2

plt

Looking at the data, it is interesting that none of the distributions look strictly normal. Some even show hints of being multimodal. Especially the distributions of Points looks like this. This could indicate that there were distinct groups of people attending the course, such as underachievers, average students, and star pupils, for example. The resultant distribution could be a sum of multiple normal distributions.

The age distribution is very asymmetric, understandably. There is a practical limit on how young people could have attended the course. The other distributions look more normally distributed, albeit slightly distorted.

The strongest correlation found in the dataset is between Attitude and Points, there is also a strong (anti-)correlation between deep and surface learning approaches, which appear to be polar opposites of each other. Actually, the surface/superficial learning strategy seems to anti-correlate with every other metric in the dataset.

Modeling the data

For the next part, I chose Attitude, stra, and surf as explanatory variables, since they showed the greatest correlation in the above analysis.

#here the data is modeled using multiple linear regression. Points is the dependent variable, Attitude,stra and surf are the explanatory variables
learning_model <- lm(Points ~ Attitude+stra+surf, data = learning2014)
summary(learning_model)

The summary shows that the Attitude variable seems to have the most significant contribution to the exam score, with the probability that the parameter is zero (that is, the null hypothesis) Pr(>|t|) = 1.93e-08. The strategic approach seems to contribute quite a bit, the value of the coefficient is high, but since the standard error of the parameter is so high, it does not have such a high significance as the other one. The statistical significance of surface approach coefficient seems to be extremely low, so we drop it from the model and model the data again.

#same as before, without surf
learning_model2 <- lm(Points ~ Attitude+stra, data = learning2014)
summary(learning_model2)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = Points ~ Attitude + stra, data = learning2014)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -17.6436  -3.3113   0.5575   3.7928  10.9295 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)  8.97290    2.39591   3.745  0.00025 ***
## Attitude     0.34658    0.05652   6.132 6.31e-09 ***
## stra         0.91365    0.53447   1.709  0.08927 .  
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 5.289 on 163 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.2048, Adjusted R-squared:  0.1951 
## F-statistic: 20.99 on 2 and 163 DF,  p-value: 7.734e-09

Looking at significance values Pr(>|t|), this model looks like a good fit, the statistical significance of both coefficients has risen from the previous model. One can interpret this model in such way, that a positive attitude towards statistics, perhaps indicative of the motivation of the student, is the most significant predictor of exam performance. There is also some indication that strategic learning approach has some contribution to exam score, but the signal is lower than it is with the attitude.

Although the reliability of the model seems to be quite high, it still does not explain that much of the variance in the data as one could hope for. This is reflected by the relatively low value of Multiple R-squared: 0.2048. It gives a proportional value, how much of the variance in the data is explained by the model. It gets values between one and zero, zero means that the model does not explain anything, one means that the model can explain all the variance in the data (in the case of a simple linear regression, this means that all the data points fall into the regression line).

Model validation

Last, I estimated the validity of the results by looking at a few diagnostic plots. R makes this quite easy. When the argument of the Plot() function is a model, it automatically assumes the user wants to create diagnostic plots. These plots give a quick way to visually inspect, whether or not the assumptions made during modeling hold.

The validity of the model can be estimated by inspecting the residuals, i.e., the differences between the model and the data. In addition to the obvious assumption, that the relation between the dependent and explanatory variables is linear, linear models also make the following assumptions about the statistical properties of the errors: The errors are normally distributed The errors are not correlated The errors have constant variance, \(\sigma^{2}\) The size of a given error does not depend on the explanatory variables

I made three plots to estimate the validity of model and the assumptions: Residuals vs Fitted values, Normal QQ-plot, and Residuals vs Leverage.

The constant variance of errors can be estimated by plotting the residuals against the fitted values. Any pattern in the plot indicates a problem. For the most part, the plot does not show any signs of such a pattern. There are, however, a few suspicious points in the lower part of the plot, that stand out as outliers.

plot(learning_model2,which=c(1))

The normality of the errors can be estimated by looking at the QQ-plot. The QQ-plot compares the quantiles of the residual distribution and the theoretical (normal) distribution against each other. The nore the points in the plot deviate from the diagonal line, the less normal the residuals are. In this case, the assumption of normality holds quite well, although the tails of the distributions seem wonder away from the line somewhat. On the lower left corner of the plot, the same outliers as in the previous one seem to be present.

plot(learning_model2,which=c(2))

The last diagnostic plot, Residuals vs leverage, is used to look if some measurements, such as outliers, have too much influence on the model parameters. In general, the plot looks good, apart from the same outliers as present in the two previous plots.

plot(learning_model2,which=c(5))

Data description

The dataset analyzed in this exercise contains student achievement data in secondary education of two Portugese schools. The data attributes include student grades, demographic, social and school related features, and it was collected by using school reports and questionnaires. Full description of the data can be found here.

Of particular intereset is the student alcohol consumption. Variable alc_use is the average of workday alcohol consumption Dalc and weekend alcohol consumption Walc. Boolean high_use is TRUE if alc_use is > 2, it is otherwise FALSE.

I have selected four interesting variables to explain the possible high/low alcohol consumption, age, sex, studytime, and Pstatus. The reasoning/interest was following: * Age: One would assume, that alcohol consumption increases with age. * Sex: Due to social expectations and perhaps peer pressure, boys will likely drink more. * Study time: A lax attitude to homework might correlate to increased alcohol consumption. * Pstatus: A more adventurous guess, whether or not the parents are living together could be a proxy for the psychological well being of the student, and in turn, alcohol use (most likely a better one would be an aggregate of multiple variables).

Logistic regression modeling

I included all the considered variables except the parent cohabitation status in the logistic regression model, since it did not seem to affect the amount the students drank.

mdl <- glm(high_use ~ sex + studytime + age, data = alc, family = "binomial")
summary(mdl)
## 
## Call:
## glm(formula = high_use ~ sex + studytime + age, family = "binomial", 
##     data = alc)
## 
## Deviance Residuals: 
##     Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max  
## -1.4737  -0.8178  -0.6672   1.1747   2.2964  
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error z value Pr(>|z|)   
## (Intercept)  -3.9603     1.7043  -2.324  0.02014 * 
## sexM          0.6687     0.2440   2.741  0.00612 **
## studytime    -0.4851     0.1594  -3.042  0.00235 **
## age           0.2225     0.1001   2.224  0.02615 * 
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## (Dispersion parameter for binomial family taken to be 1)
## 
##     Null deviance: 465.68  on 381  degrees of freedom
## Residual deviance: 435.64  on 378  degrees of freedom
## AIC: 443.64
## 
## Number of Fisher Scoring iterations: 4

The model shows that each of the selected variables have predictive power, as the statistical significance of each model parameter is at least < 0.05. The intercept is quite low, which is follows from the fact that we included age in the regression; since the students are at least 15-16 year old, the positive contribution from age needs to be balanced by a negative intercept. The negative coefficient for study time shows that the amount of studying correlates negatively with the alcohol consumption, whereas being male has an positive effect on the likelihood of excessive drinking (it seems that R has automatically assigned a numerical value 0.0 to females and 1.0 to males in order to perform the regression).

library(DescTools)
OR <- coef(mdl) %>% exp
CI <- MeanCI(OR)
cbind(OR, CI)
## Warning in cbind(OR, CI): number of rows of result is not a multiple of vector
## length (arg 2)
##                     OR         CI
## (Intercept) 0.01905673  0.9589365
## sexM        1.95179032 -0.3632318
## studytime   0.61565757  2.2811048
## age         1.24924140  0.9589365

The same interpretation can be made from the odds ratios. Since odds > 1 are positively associated with success, both male sex and age increase the probability of a student drinking much, the opposite is true for studying much OR = 0.62 (< 1.0).

Testing the predictive power of the model

Last, I tested the models predictive power by calculating the probability of high alcohol use using the original data set, and then comparing the result to the actual value. The results can be summarized in a so-called confusion matrix, which tabulates the predictions versus the ground truth.

probabilities <- predict(mdl, type = "response")
alc <- mutate(alc, probability = probabilities)
alc <- mutate(alc, prediction = probability>0.5) 
alc %>% group_by(high_use,prediction) %>% summarise(ratio = n())
## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'high_use' (override with `.groups` argument)
## # A tibble: 4 x 3
## # Groups:   high_use [2]
##   high_use prediction ratio
##   <lgl>    <lgl>      <int>
## 1 FALSE    FALSE        251
## 2 FALSE    TRUE          17
## 3 TRUE     FALSE         95
## 4 TRUE     TRUE          19

The values in the summary are the amounts of true and false positives, and true and false negatives. The 0.71 accuracy (accuracy = (TP+TN)/Ntot)) of this model seems to me surprisingly good (considering my low expectations). For a coin toss, the value would be 0.5. On the other hand, the relatively good accuracy is explained by the low number of false positives. The number of false negatives is quite high, so overall this model is not so good in finding out students with a risk of high alcohol consumption.

Everything seems to be in order. Next I checked the data correlations and distributions.

#Let's have a looksie. Since there are quite a few variables, plot each

There appear to be clear correlations between some of the variables. This is quite expected, since, for instance, industrial areas (indus) are more likely to be more polluted (nox). Also it is not that surprising, that more expensive neighbourhoods have less crime (medv vs crim), and sub urbs with residents of lower socio-economic status (lstat) have higher rates of crime.

Looking at the histograms, it is quite clear that only some of the variables appear to be normally distributed, whereas most are not. This is actually quite worrying, since the fundamental assumption of linear discriminant analysis is that the exploratory variables are normally distributed. Nevertheless, we boldly proceed.

The scale() function does column-wise operations to the data. First it removes the mean from each column and then divides the residuals with their standard deviation.

Next I created a new categorical variable from the crime rate by creating quantiles according to how high or low the crime rate was. For model validation, the data was also split into test and training sets.

bins <- quantile(boston_scaled$crim)

# remove original crim from the dataset
boston_scaled <- dplyr::select(boston_scaled, -crim)

n <- nrow(boston_scaled)
# choose randomly 80% of the rows
ind <- sample(n,  size = n * 0.8)
# create train set
train <- boston_scaled[ind,]
# create test set 
test <- boston_scaled[-ind,]

Linear discriminant analysis

Next, I applied linear discriminant analysis (LDA) to the training data. LDA is a statistical method that tries to separate two or more classes of objects by finding a linear combination of features that can be used as an optimal separator.

# linear discriminant analysis
#crime is the target variable, . indicates that all the other are explanatory 
#variables
lda.fit <- lda(crime ~ . , data = train)

# print the lda.fit object
lda.fit

K-means clustering

To further analyze the data, I applied K-means clustering to the dataset.

#Since the Boston dataset is untouched, it can be used as-is.
#Rewrite the boston_scaled variable
boston_scaled <- as.data.frame(scale(Boston))

#Check out the distance measures
dist_boston <- dist(Boston)
summary(dist_boston)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   1.119  85.624 170.539 226.315 371.950 626.047
km <-kmeans(boston_scaled, centers = 4)
pairs(boston_scaled[c("crim","medv","dis","rm")], col=km$cluster)

An important part of clustering is to actually determine, what is the optimal number of clusters. It can be estimated from the the total cluster sum of squares. The optimum number can be found where the sum changes radically.

k_max <- 10
# calculate the total within sum of squares
twcss <- sapply(1:k_max, function(k){kmeans(boston_scaled, k)$tot.withinss})

# visualize the results
qplot(x = 1:k_max, y = twcss, geom = 'line')

km <-kmeans(boston_scaled, centers = 2)
pairs(boston_scaled[c("crim","medv","dis","rm")], col=km$cluster)

In this case, the optimum number of clusters appeared to be 2. Two clusters clearly separate the dataset to areas, where the crime is virtually non-existent, and to areas, where there is crime.

Using K-means clusters to classify the data for linear discriminant analysis

As a quick experiment, I checked, how it would look if I used the clusters from K-means as classifiers for the linear discriminant analysis.

## Warning in lda.default(x, grouping, ...): variables are collinear
lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}


#plot(lda.fit,dimen=2,col = clusters,pch = clusters)
plot(lda.fit,dimen=2,col = clusters,pch = clusters)+lda.arrows(lda.fit,myscale=2.0)

## integer(0)

It seems the sub-urban areas are divided quite strongly into industrial areas (indu) and areas predominately populated by black people (black=(1000(Bk - 0.63)^2 where Bk is the proportion of blacks by town. ), as these seem to be the strongest linear separators.

Exercise 5 - Dimensionality reduction

In this exercise we used data that was wrangled together from human development and gender inequality data by country. We have variables:

  • country
  • edu2F (Proportion of females with at least secondary education)
  • labourF (Proportion of females in the labour force)
  • exp.edu (Expected years of schooling, both sexes)
  • life.exp (average life expectancy)
  • GNI (Gross National Income per capita)
  • mat.mort(Maternal mortality ratio)
  • ado.birth (Adolescent birth rate)
  • parl.rep (Percetange of female representatives in parliament)

Reading in and checking the data

#load libraries
library(dplyr); library(GGally)

human <- read.table("./data/human.txt",header=TRUE)
# First, check that the data is OK. Should be 155 obs and 8 variables
dim(human)
## [1] 155   8
ggpairs(human)

Many of the distributions seem to be normal, or at least they are a blend of normal distribution and something else. Some of the more skewed distributions appear also to be normal, but they are only capped at the left hand side (GNI, maternal mortality, for instance). There are quite a few strong correlations (education increases life expectancy). GNI has a tendency to correlate with just about everything, but there is a weird phenomenon, that for some variables, the correlation appears to be more like a condition than an explanation (for the lack of a better word). For example, maternal mortality can be high only if GNI is low, but a low GNI does not predict explicitly, what the maternal mortality will be.

Principal component analysis

After checking that the data set was OK, I applied principal component analysis to the data:

pca_human <- prcomp(human)
biplot(pca_human, choices = 1:2,cex=0.4,scale=2.0)

OK, that looked a bit messy, and GNI dominates the first principal component too much. The second principal component seems to deal with variables that contain a certain dichotomy between developed and non-developed countries. Standardizing the variables might help:

human_std <- scale(human)
pca_human <- prcomp(human_std)
biplot(pca_human, choices = 1:2,cex=0.4,scale=2.0,xlab="Wealth", ylab="Gender roles")

Scaling seemed to help somewhat, but the plot is still quite terrible (sorry!). With some zooming and scaling following interpretations can be made:

  • Principal component 1 could be described as something like an industrialization, or wealth index. In the countries on the left-hand side have women have more education, the child mortality is low etc.. On the right-hand side, countries are poorer, the child mortality is higher and there are more adolescents giving birth to children.
  • The second principal component shows how much women participate in the society in general, both in governmental roles and also int the general workforce.
  • Western and some African countries have a high percentage of females in active roles in the society
  • Middle-eastern (or maybe islamic?) countries, even if they might be moderately wealthy, are much more male dominated than the other countries.

Analysis of longitudinal data

Data wrangling

First, run the data wrangling script created earlier

RATSL <- read.table("./data/RATSL.txt")
BPRSL <- read.table("./data/BPRSL.txt")

#Data must be "re-factored" :P
BPRSL$treatment <- factor(BPRSL$treatment)
BPRSL$subject <- factor(BPRSL$subject)

RATSL$Group <- factor(RATSL$Group)
RATSL$ID <- factor(RATSL$ID)

The data was transformed during wrangling from wide to long form. What this means, is that it groups together and turns several variables (for example, week1,week2, etc.,) into one variable (week), that has multiple values (1,2,3, etc.). Basically, the process creates a time series from those variables (this is just because the dimension of the variable is time in this case).

Rat data

The first data set is from a rat nutrition study. The three groups were put on different diets, and each animals body weight (grams) was recorded repeatedly (approximately weekly, except in week seven when two recordings were taken) over a 9-week period.

First, I plotted the data without any scaling

library(ggplot2)
ggplot(RATSL, aes(x = RATSL$time, y = RATSL$weight, linetype = ID)) +  geom_line() +  scale_linetype_manual(values = rep(1:10, times=4)) +  facet_grid(. ~ Group, labeller = label_both) +  theme(legend.position = "none") + scale_x_continuous(name="Time [d]")  + scale_y_continuous(name="Weight [g]",limits = c(min(RATSL$weight), max(RATSL$weight)))

Next, I checked how scaling affects the data. I took the average of the weight of every rats at each time point in order to see, what kind of systematic trend is there (or not). Error bars are given by the average error of the mean.

n <- RATSL$time %>% unique() %>% length()
n=11
RATSL_scaled <- RATSL %>% group_by(Group, time) %>% summarise( mean = mean(weight), se = sd(weight )/sqrt(n)) %>% ungroup()

ggplot(RATSL_scaled, aes(x = time, y = mean, linetype=Group, shape = Group)) +
    geom_line() +
    geom_errorbar(aes(ymin=mean-se, ymax=mean+se, linetype="1"), width=1)+ scale_y_continuous(name="Weight [g]")+scale_x_continuous(name="Time [d]")

## Summary measure analysis

We check the effect of the diet by comparing mean of the differences of the first and the last weight measurement, i.e., it is the summary measure.

#get the first and last weights

first_weight <-RATSL %>% filter(time==min(time)) %>% select(weight, Group, ID)
last_weight <- RATSL %>% filter(time==max(time)) %>% select(weight, Group, ID)
RATSL_summary <- select(first_weight,Group,ID) 
RATSL_summary$first_weight <- first_weight$weight #this was done afterwards :)
RATSL_summary$weight_gain <- last_weight$weight-first_weight$weight


# Draw a boxplot of the mean versus treatment
ggplot(RATSL_summary, aes(x = Group, y = weight_gain)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  stat_summary(fun.y = "difference", geom = "point", shape=23, size=4, fill = "white")

There appears to be one outlier in group 2, so that will be removed

RATSL_fout <- filter(RATSL_summary, !(weight_gain<30 & Group ==2))


# Draw a boxplot of the mean versus treatment
ggplot(RATSL_fout, aes(x = Group, y = weight_gain)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  stat_summary(fun.y = "difference", geom = "point", shape=23, size=4, fill = "white")

There are clearly differences between the groups, and the removal of the outlier clearly accentuated those differences.

BPRS data

This data set is taken from Davis (2002). Here 40 male subjects were randomly assigned to one of two treatment groups and each subject was rated on the brief psychiatric rating scale (BPRS) measured before treatment began (week 0) and then at weekly intervals for eight weeks. The BPRS assesses the level of 18 symptom constructs such as hostility, suspiciousness, hallucinations and grandiosity; each of these is rated from one (not present) to seven (extremely severe). The scale is used to evaluate patients suspected of having schizophrenia.

Here is the plot of the treatment progress

ggplot(BPRSL, aes(x = BPRSL$week, y = BPRSL$bprs, linetype = subject)) +  geom_line() +  scale_linetype_manual(values = rep(1:10, times=4)) +  facet_grid(. ~ treatment, labeller = label_both) +  theme(legend.position = "none") + scale_x_continuous(name="Week")  + scale_y_continuous(name="BPRS")

## Multiple R-squared:  0.1851, Adjusted R-squared:  0.1806 
## F-statistic: 40.55 on 2 and 357 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

The model clearly shows, that the treatment group has no significant effect on the outcome, but the bprs score decreases very strongly with time.

Random intercept model

Since the previous model assumes that the results of the measurements are independent of each other, and with repeated measurements of the same subjects, this is clearly not true. A better choice is the random intercept model

library(lme4)

ri_model <- lmer(bprs ~ week + treatment + (1 | subject), data=BPRSL, REML = FALSE)
summary(ri_model)

Random intercept and random slope model with interaction

Finally, we allow interaction between the time and treatment

rirswi_model <- lmer(bprs ~ week + treatment + week*treatment + (week | subject), data=BPRSL, REML = FALSE)

The plots are admittedly a bit clumsy, for some reason, there is a linestyle related error if I dont divide the plots according to the treatment type.
